Great — this is a very important low-level question 👍

🧠 Who Does Sector Conversion?
👉 Short Answer:
Filesystem + Block Layer together handle it

But let’s make it crystal clear 👇

📦 Step-by-Step Responsibility
✅ 1. Filesystem (e.g., ext4)
Works in block units (usually 4KB)

Does:

Offset → Logical Block → Physical Block
👉 At this point:

It still thinks in blocks, NOT sectors

✅ 2. Block Layer (⭐ Main role here)
👉 This is where sector conversion actually happens

Block layer knows:

Disk sector size (512B / 4KB)

Device capabilities

So it converts:

Physical Block → Sector
Example:

Block size = 4KB
Sector size = 512B

1 block = 8 sectors

Physical Block 100
→ Sector = 100 × 8 = 800
👉 This value is what goes into:

BIO

Request queue

Driver

✅ 3. Device Driver
Uses sector numbers directly

Builds hardware command like:

Read from sector 800
👉 Driver does NOT calculate mapping, it just uses it

🎯 Final Responsibility Split
Filesystem → Block Mapping (logical → physical block)

⭐ Block Layer → Sector Conversion (block → sector)

Driver → Executes sector read
⚡ One-Line Answer (Interview)
👉 “Sector conversion is handled by the block layer, using device sector size, after filesystem maps logical blocks to physical blocks.”

🔥 Key Insight (Very Important)
Filesystem: "Where is data?" (blocks)

Block layer: "How to talk to disk?" (sectors)

